  "prompt": "What is the function of centrosomes in plant cells?",
  "response": "Centrosomes play a crucial role in animal cells by organizing microtubules and facilitating cell division through the formation of the mitotic spindle. However, **plant cells do not have centrosomes**. Instead, plant cells rely on alternative mechanisms to organize microtubules and carry out cell division.\n\nIn plant cells:\n\n1. **Microtubule Organization**: Microtubules are organized by structures called **microtubule-organizing centers (MTOCs)**, which are dispersed throughout the cell rather than concentrated in a single centrosome-like structure.\n2. **Cell Division**: During mitosis, plant cells use a **phragmoplast** to guide the formation of the new cell wall between daughter cells, and microtubules are organized along the cell membrane and around the nucleus.\n3. **Spindle Formation**: The spindle apparatus in plant cells forms without centrosomes, with microtubules nucleating from the nuclear envelope and other cytoplasmic sites.\n\nThus, while centrosomes are essential in animal cells, plant cells have evolved different mechanisms to achieve microtubule organization and cell division.",
